huntBios.GENERAL_INFORMATION:
This hunt occurs during the General Season Any Bull elk hunt.  This hunt is intended to help reduce this elk herd. This unit is currently over objective by over 2,000 elk because a large number of the elk on this unit move onto the adjacent Ute tribal lands where there is little to no hunting pressure and no public access. The elk that move onto the tribal lands often stay there with no hunting pressure all fall and winter. At least half of the elk on the unit have learned to move onto the tribal lands as soon as hunting pressure starts in Sept. and the rest will trickle down throughout the fall. During this hunt, the majority of the elk on the unit are moving onto Tribal Lands and may stay there unless the weather cooperates and they drift back up onto the Forest Service lands.  Hunters should be aware of the Ute tribal lands and learn the boundaries.  Public hunting is not permitted on tribal lands but hunting near the tribal boundary are usually the best areas to hunt.  There are no CWMUs on this unit.  
The unit includes the High Uintas Wilderness area, but many of the elk will be moving down out of the wilderness prior to or during this hunt.
Road access on the unit is limited to mostly canyon bottoms due to the steepness of the terrain.
huntBios.SAFETY_CONS: Be prepared for sudden severe weather changes during this hunt.
huntBios.WEATHER_CONS: Weather can vary during this hunt from hot and dry to cold and snowy.  Be prepared for either extreme.  Be prepared for muddy roads.

huntBios.BIOLOGIST_NOTES:
Elk on this unit move down in elevation for the winter and they winter primarily on Ute tribal Lands and on south facing slopes at lower elevation on the Forest Service lands. The elk move towards the tribal land boundary as soon as they get much hunting pressure starting in Sept. There is very little hunting pressure on the tribal lands so elk have learned to go there as soon as hunting pressure starts. They will also move into difficult to access areas on the Forest. Locating elk on public land is the real key for this hunt. Remember that you are also able to hunt elk on private land on this unit if you can gain written permission. Recommended areas in the South Slope, Yellowstone: There are numerous suggested areas to hunt on this unit. The suggested areas to hunt include (starting on the west side of the unit and working east):

Soapstone Basin and Lightening Ridge- Good road access, but usually fairly popular and the roads are heavily traveled all summer so the elk move away from the areas with roads
North Fork of the Duchesne- paved road access in the lower main canyon, tribal lands down low Blind Stream- limited road access, tribal land down low Rock Creek- paved road access, steep areas Pigeon Water- popular area but hunters must be aware of the tribal boundary Lake Fork/Moon Lake- paved road access, some private property along the paved road Yellowstone- need to be aware of tribal boundary 77 Flat/Burnt Mill- a little flatter area, be aware of tribal boundary, hunt along the tribal boundary Dry Gulch- usually has elk this time of year near the tribal boundary Uinta Canyon- tribal lands down low, Lower Pole Creek area has been good in recent years Farm Creek- will likely need to get away from roads to find the elk, has been a good area the last couple years Whiterocks Canyon- Whiterocks River is the eastern unit boundary, steep terrain, usually some elk in the rough canyons north of Farm Creek trail head area Private Lands areas that usually have elk during this hunt: Arcadia, north side of Tabiona, Talmage, Mtn. Home, Altonah, Bluebell, Neola all have elk that come down off of the tribal land and onto private property when there is enough snow. If it snows early there may be land owners willing to let the public hunt elk if they move onto their private lands.

huntBoundaryInfos.LAND_OWNERSHIP: Public lands are all Forest Service lands managed by the Ashley and Uinta-Wasatch-Cache National Forests.  This unit includes a large portion of the High Uintas Wilderness Area where all motor vehicles are prohibited.  This unit also includes large tracts of Ute tribal lands that are closed to non-tribal members.  The tribal lands are mostly the lower elevation sagebrush zone but in some areas they reach up into the aspen/conifer zone.  There is a large amount of private property on the unit too.  Most of the private property is below the tribal boundary but there are several parcels of private property in the canyon bottoms.
huntBoundaryInfos.WMA_IN_UNIT: Little Montes Creek WMA north of Ballard and Kevin Conway WMA southeast of Myton.  Elk, bear and cougar are rarely found on these WMAs.
huntBoundaryInfos.CAMPGRND_INFO:
All Campgrounds on this unit are managed by the US Forest Service. Camping outside of official campgrounds is also permitted on most of the forest. There are special restrictions on camping and campfires in certain areas within the Wilderness area. Please direct all questions regarding campground availability and other camping questions to the US Forest Service. Maps and camping regulations are available on their websites.
Ashley National Forest website: http://www.fs.usda.gov/ashley
Uinta-Wasatch-Cache National Forest website: http://www.fs.usda.gov/uwcnf
huntBoundaryInfos.PRIM_ACCESS_PTS: The main access points for the High Uintas Wilderness include: Uinta Canyon Trailhead, West Fork of Whiterocks Trailhead, Chepeta Trailhead, Lake Fork Trailhead, Yellowstone/Swift Creek Trailhead, Jackson Park road, Dry Gulch road, Rock Creek Trailhead, North Fork of Duchesne Trailhead, and Grandview trailheads
huntBoundaryInfos.SUGGESTED_MAPS: USGS 1:100,000 Kings Peak and Duchesne topo maps
huntBoundaryInfos.ATV_VEH_ACCESS: All roads and ATV trails on this unit are managed by the US Forest Service and are covered on their Travel Management Plans. Please direct all questions regarding which roads and trails ATVs can be operated on to the US Forest Service. Maps can also be purchased online at:http://www.fs.usda.gov/ashley
huntBoundaryInfos.PRIV_TRIBE_LAND_ISSUES: The hunt unit does not include the Ute tribal lands.  There is a large tract of Ute tribal trust land that stretches east to west across the South Slope of the Uinta Mountains.  Road access across the tribal land is permitted only across the main access roads to the Forest.  All ATVs are prohibited on tribal Lands, they must be trailered on access roads across tribal Lands.
